<rate>5< /rate>< review>
I don't know how to put this any other way, but this is one of the most special places I have ever been too.  This might seem a little extreme for a tea shop; however, Sophie's Cuppa Tea is a sanctuary of peace and serenity.  The owners, Bei and John, are two of the most incredible people I have ever met and they also serve the best tea I have ever had.  I can promise everyone that they will not be disappointed if they come to this shop.   In addition to the shop, if you are looking for your next vacation, ask them about their yearly China Tea Trip.  It is a once in a life time opportunity (although I plan on going every year!).  See photos below :). BTW: They have amazing snacks and salads (fresh and organic).<//review>

< username>
P. I.</username>
<text>Stepping through the door of this beautifully curated spot in Montclair, is essentially stepping into another world, a world of beautiful art, rare porcelain, and even finer teas.
Lovingly tended by John and Sophie,  Tea masters, who have a deep knowledge tea based on regular travel to Fujian as well as other ancient tea sources in China, I was treated to simply the best large glass of simply Wu Long, (Their spelling, I have no knowledge whatsoever of Mandarin) that I've ever had, and was also treated to a rare sight. I have seen tea wheels but none larger than the one I was presented with At Cuppa Tea, easily 30 inches in diameter,, with a specially made tea wheel stand you will only find here, because they had it made especially for their tea wheels.
The decor and mood in the place was an absolute oasis of calm and tranquility in a ever-maddening world, (Even in Montclair)  and is now on my to-do list every time I am in the neighborhood.
I'd try the Wu Long, however, their green tea selection, ( I am a Jasmine pearl fanatic) is simply a marvel of tea curation, and John, was a gracious and knowledgeable host,  with an affable manner sometimes missing in high level tea establishments, and I ended up leaving with a rare Jasmine, as well as a vastly improved attitude, as will you when you visit John and Sophie's Cuppa Tea in Montclair.  Treat yourself to some relaxation!</text><Response>None</Response>< GmapID>

<Text>A real gem. Sophie's is more than a place to enjoy a cuppa tea. It's an experience and a community where everyone's welcome. It's like a favorite local pub, but instead of pints and salty snacks, it's rare Chinese teas and delicious pastries. The owners' Saturday tastings and talks reveal the immense world of Chinese teas. John and Bei source their teas by traveling to China so they're deeply knowledgeable, passionate, and a joy to talk with. If you have an interest in learning about tea, or just want a great place to rest and read, you should stop in.< /Text>< pictures>
None< /pictures>

108824308973432510135</user>
<username>j. rodman<//username>< time>
1480204973861< /time>
< rate>
3<//rate>
<Text>Tea selection and quality are good, far above what you'd get at a Peet's etc.  However, I wasn't amazed with my wulong, having had better experiences at e.g. Imperial Tea Court or ordering from Red Blossom.  Perhaps the comparison is unfair, and it's certainly the best tea you'll find in a walk-in store for at least a 6-mile radius.

Presentation is a little westernized receiving the brewed tea in a mug with no possibility to experience the progression of flavor as a gaiwan would offer.

The real downside though is the noise.  It was impossible to focus on my tea with a ridiculous conversation going on a few feet away.  By comparison, Peet's down at Lakeshore has a moderate hubbub going on at times, but is far easier to ignore and read, or participate if so inclined. I'm not sure if this could be solved with decor / sound-muting panelling or similar.

Unfortunately the overall verdict is it's not worth the trip just to buy tea to take home when there are so many other high quality options in Berkeley & San Francisco, and it's not a pleasant environment to spend time in contemplation or reading unless at an unpopular time.  If I lived in the neighborhood I might make it a habit.< /Text>< Pics>
None</Pics>

None< /response>

Last spring, when I first tried to contact Creative Energy - Richmond I couldn't get an answer on the phone or a response to left messages. I had to call Creative Energy - San Mateo to ask the Richmond store to contact men. I was finally able to order a new cover in July and paid the deposit in September. Today is Nov. 1 and the cover has still not arrived. I have not heard a word as to status.

In September we had a "contract" repair person come because the heater was not working. He repaired the heater, and then sent a $2500 estimate for "needed repairs." When I inquired if the additions were a) essential to replace, or b) expected to need replacement. I received the following note. "Randy inspected spa.  Found faulty heater, ozone, and control panel is starting to get blurry. Will send estimate for repair.  He suggested heater because spa wasn‚Äôt heating.  Ozone isn‚Äôt completely necessary.  It helps the chlorine to work better. He suggested the control panel because it was starting to get blurry."  We are still left unclear how to proceed.

I would suggest that some customer service training is in order.</review>

I hired Creative Energy to move our hot tub (purchased from Creative Energy many years ago) from our old house to our new one.  The workers were easy to get along with and very competent, and were careful not to damage my plants.  I had originally intended to level the surface at the new house, but they pointed out that the slope was gradual enough that I probably didn't need to do so, thereby saving us money.  Charged a reasonable price for the job.  One criticism:  they arrived late, outside the scheduled time window.  While there was a good reason for the delay, they did not, and should have, called to warn me that they would be late.<//Text>

<Response>None</Response><text>This is the worst interaction I've had with a business, possibly ever.

Had an issue with my hottub, called to schedule an appoint, it took me sending several unresponded to emails to actually hear back and get an appointment schedule (I would soon find out this is basically their status-quo for communication), they had also made me plain-text send my credit card info over email because apparently they have no more sophisticated way of actually taking this info.

Finally got something scheduled, the technician determined the heater had broken, but did not have the necessary part so would have to schedule another appointment, and that Creative would reach out to schedule that since they'll know the part number etc. No big deal, the technician himself was actually great, and seemed effective at their job, and was happy to explain their process in diagnosing the issue (this would end up being the only positive impression I have for the entire company).

It is at this point I get no communication for a few days still, until finally receiving a "Here is your quote, please acknowledge this to confirm" type email. I respond promptly and hear nothing for four or five days, I message again and continue to get ZERO response for almost a week, until I email yet a third time, to which FOUR DAYS after that I finally get an email.

This email which has now come over 2 weeks later-- with 4 unanswered emails from me to them-- contains an encrypted zip file, and a message with a password to the zip file, saying to please open and follow the instructions.

This seems very questionable but I just want my hottub working again and I'm too exhausted with their customer service to reply and wait possibly weeks again for a response. I open the zip file in a computer I don't mind reformatting (since i'm feeling very suspect to this random zip) and find a nonsense microsoft word document.

I message back explaining I have no idea how they want me to move forward, and if they can give me ANY ETA AT ALL as to when this second appointment can get scheduled. Once again I hear nothing for 2 or 3 days, until I get an email:
"Sorry. We got hacked. Please don't open it. Please, make sure your anti-virus software is up-to-date"

The company I have had an extremely difficult time communicating with, who made me plain-text email my credit card info, ignored my messages until finally sending me a virus, appologizing while STILL NOT GIVING ANY ETA OR RESPONSE TO MY ACTUAL UNDERLYING ISSUE.

I finally get a relevant email from them yet another day or two later explaining that the supplier doesn't have the part in stock, but they should "early next week", and they will reach out then. (you already know what happens next)

Over two more weeks pass, with me sending four completely ignored emails, until FINALLY I get an email of them asking if I'd like to schedule friday morning, I'm completely exhausted with them, and just relieved to actually have a date scheduled.

Today is that Friday, and lo and behold, I get another email from them, saying their technician is ill, and will not be able to come in for the repair.

I have no idea how this establishment has so many positive reviews, I can only assume it's their friends and family pumping with fake reviews, along with a slew of bot reviews that they've paid for. My ask for this company was an extremely trivial and reasonable one, it's not like I had some esoteric hottub, or esoteric issue with my hottub.

I would urge ANYONE who reads this to please consider LITERALLY ANYWHERE ELSE for their hottub or spa needs, unless you don't mind waiting months for nothing to actually happen. This has been the absolute worst interaction i've had with a small business, worse than any interaction I've had with big businesses for that matter.</text>< pics>

<Text>As with most of the places in LAX, I think this restaurant is a concept provided by the chef(s) and executed by a separate company under license. In this case Michael Voltaggio has leant his ‚ÄúInk‚Äù brand to LAX in the form of his second branch of Ink.Sack, his LA sandwich shop. What is great about this place is that the prices seem to be the same here as outside of the airport - $6.99 for a sandwich. And with most sandwiches, as long as the ingredients are good, it can be assembled in quick order without too much difficulty. The place was quiet when I went and pickup was very quick. A Jose Andres was ordered, one of the cold sandwiches they offer and I was on my way.

On the flight I opened the sandwich and it was still in good condition, despite there being a vinaigrette, it wasn‚Äôt soggy and the ham and chorizo married well with the olives and manchego. A good sandwich that went well with the bottle of whatever wine offered on board.

If you‚Äôre looking for something that will satisfy you on the flight, take a look here, it‚Äôll help with any hunger pangs in the middle of the night.<//Text>< Pics>

I had been here previously and the experience was less than 5 star. This most recent visit however, was fantastic. We were there during evening when sunlight was making mosaic view difficult because of the reflection‚Ä¶

< Review>
Nice little spot to take pictures and get an amazing view of the ocean to the West of San Francisco. It can get a little busy at times, so if you're taking photos you will need a little patience. Tips for taking photos:

Bring a telephoto lens to get some nice shots of the ocean, or a lens with a fast aperture to blur out the crowds in the back. The colors are nice, so be sure to capture them! Otherwise, great little spot to checkout.<//Review>

Heights neighborhood. Started in 2003 and completed in 2005, this was a neighbor guided by two artists. It is truly a work of art. Surrounding the steps are beautifully cared for gardens. This used to be a hidden wonder in the city, but word is out and it gets a bit busy. Very hard to find a moment to get a photo of the whole set of stairs empty of people. Very worth coming here. Oh, and when you are at the top of the steps, go a little further to the Grand View Lookout...beautiful views.

Remember this is a residential neighbourhood and be sure to be respectful.<//Review></record></dataset><record>

< text>
Beautiful concept of stairs at public place. We enjoyed it very much. Cactus garden around staircase is also amazing. Not much rush. Careful in parking to avoid theft. Must visit place in San Francisco. Tiles concept is also well thought, the Sun - The Moon - water reservoir (sea) , water flow (river), water animals & then land all are beautifully presented< /text>

It‚Äôs a very touristy spot, but with reason. Not only are the steps gorgeous and so interesting to look at all the details of, the views are impeccable. You get to see the ocean, the golden gate park, and even a glimpse of the bridge in the distance. If you go all the way up, you‚Äôll find overlook park which is yet another climb, but it allows you to see a 360 view of San Fran. Even the downtown area far away!</review>

<Review>One of the best lookouts in the city. Walking up the steps can be pretty tiring but rest assured that the views of the Sunset District backdropped by the foggy shores of the Pacific Ocean are well worth the climb. For the best views, come near sunset. A bit of a warning: there is nowhere to leave your bike, meaning you may have to carry your bike up the stairs (like I did) to ensure it doesn't get stolen at the bottom - apparently thievery is a problem in the area.< /Review>< Name>

< Time>
1512581502870<//Time>
<Review>These steps are gorgeous. I love how the scene moves from the sea, to the earth, to the night sky, to the sun. The walk isn't too strenuous, either. You definitely need to be ambulatory and in fairly descent shape to get all the way up, but I feel like a spry 5 or 6 year-old could handle it easily. There isn't somewhere to sit and chill after the climb or something like a park to hang out in; these are literally just really pretty tiled steps in the middle of a residential neighborhood. Street parking is fairly easy in the area, especially if you have a smaller car.<//Review>< username>
Ashleigh Nelson<//username>

5<//rating>
< Review>
This staircase was amazing. It is one of my favorite things we saw during our sightseeing vacation.  Every stair edge was a masterpiece. There were four of us there taking pictures (two of the people were professional photographers) and none of the pictures that any of the four of us took look the same. We could have spent far more time here looking at each of the images from the staircase. This is a must see.  Unfortunately there were signs all over these streets that said car break-ins happen at this location with regularity. So do not leave anything on the seat of your car in order to avoid that!!  There was broken windshield glass curbside in multiple spots.</Review>

< text>
A nice little spot to visit, located in a residential neighborhood with not much else nearby. It's very popular, so if you manage to park, watch out for break in's. There are also signs warning people about this. You might have to wait a bit to get a solo shot, as there are always people walking up and down, but the view from the top is amazing and the staircase is gorgeous (especially during sunset).<//text>

< Review>
This is a beautiful location and a good workout! These steps were built by the community and it is a treasure ‚ù§Ô∏è. The mosaic starts from the sea, and goes all the way to the starts. The colors are vibrant and the design is magical. It is also cool to see the names of the contributors on the steps. Once you get to the top, you get a gorgeous view of the ocean and Golden Gate Park.< /Review>

<Review>A nice walk along raised road from mosaic steps and beautiful houses leads to the tiled steps from the main tram along the road. The best place for sunsets with a view of the vast and panaromic Pacific ocean, houses arranged in a beautiful array descending to the beach and roads that demarcate and hive pattern to the already amazing view. The tiled steps are beautiful in themselves and offer some great golden hour shots.< /Review><time>1564843130946< /time>< user_name>

Really cool spot to visit. Lots of young tourist from the east trying to snap selfies, which gets annoying. Hard to get any good pics with out a duck face in the background. Parking is tuff as always in San Fran. The hills are steep so make sure you use your parking brake! Make the hike to the top, great views 360¬∞. Remember, there are private residence all around so be respectful!<//review>

< Text>
I loved it! I think its a must stop if you visit San Francisco. It was on the way to our hotel... you don't have to stay long and parking was pretty easy... there are signs that say to not leave valuables in the car while you visit the steps.. just an fyi. Lovely pictures! And there is a nice view at the top.. when there isn't fog< /Text>

<UserId.>117561919292626814313</UserId.><user_name>Jacky< /user_name>< time>
1542082958282</time>
<rating>5<//rating>< text>
Another location for mosaic steps. This seemed to be much more popular and you can definitely tell because of the burglary signs posted all over. The signs tell you to beware of people breaking into your car while you are checking the tiled steps.

This place wasn't that busy, so it was easy to get photos without anyone else on the steps. People seemed to be nice about it by waiting at the bottom to let everyone get their shots in. Just know that you'd be waiting for people to go up and down the entire stairway before you'd get a clear shot.

Found parking around kirkham.< /text>

<Time>1571870505709< /Time><rating>5< /rating>< Text>
Great place to look at and take a picture of but trying to get a picture without anyone on  the steps is difficult. I got the clearest I could get just a family in the middle around 2pm but there were people coming and going the whole time. I would say come early in the morning to get a clear picture or head to the Hidden Garden Steps down the road it is a lot quieter.<//Text>

< review>
Very beautiful steps. Every flight of steps has its own picture. It is amazing to climb up the stairs and to enjoy the colorful tiled pictures.

When you get up, you can enjoy the picturesque view of the ocean and San Francisco as a reward. The best time to take great photos here is before sunset.<//review>

< text>
Nothing too special so I certainly wouldn't go out of my way to see these. However, if you are in the area they are fun and the views from the top expansive. Just beware that there are multiple signs around the bottom warning of thefts from any cars left unattended. The stories I heard suggest that this is serious!< /text>

< Review>
This is a beautiful location and a good workout! These steps were built by the community and it is a treasure ‚ù§Ô∏è. The mosaic starts from the sea, and goes all the way to the starts. The colors are vibrant and the design is magical. It is also cool to see the names of the contributors on the steps. Once you get to the top, you get a gorgeous view of the ocean and Golden Gate Park.</Review>

< text>
Unfortunately this spot is missing in many guided tours and travel guides. Nevertheless it is worth a stop. The steps go up to the Grand View park from where you have an amazing view on the Pacific, the Golden Gate park and Twin Peaks.< /text>

<Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOVMNx96nK8hRmgXuSG3Ckfe9vbbgTj23KuYDuJ=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOeFF8mNGpv3UNGaAog4tPjCREqKAuM1U4CDOoi=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOLGhxe3dF7C77iPA7Nww3ycTD5yKP52Hq-veu9=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pics>< userid>

<name>Simon Ninon</name><Date>1504805865917< /Date>< Gmap_id>
0x80858761c278b065:0x3d5b0419554cd6ed< /Gmap_id>
<rate>5<//rate>< Review>
This is a really nice artwork worth to stop by if you happen to have some time (consider that parking is reaaaaally easy and free in this area).

There are a series of multiple stairs, all decorated with beautiful and shiny mosaic. The artwork is pretty easy to get: the lowest stairs picture the sea and as you climb them, the mosaic pictures higher and higher elements: ground, sky, space, moon and sun.

It is a bit crowdy, so quite difficult to take pics of the stairs themselves, but still good to appreciate the artwork.

The view from the top is awesome, especially if you take the time to also visit the small park right after, on the top of the hill. That's why I belive that perfect time to visit that place would be sunset or sunrise (probably sunrise is better if you want to avoid the crowd, but I can't tell as I visited it during sunset).<//Review>

< rating>
5</rating>
< text>
This is one of my favorite places to go for my walks in the morning. It's like paradise,  seeing all the beautiful succulents alongside the steps and then being able to capture the view at the very top! When you get to the top of the mosaic steps, cross the street and walk to the right to climb the rest of the steps to an amazing 360 view of the city!<//text>

< review>
Very beautiful steps. Every flight of steps has its own picture. It is amazing to climb up the stairs and to enjoy the colorful tiled pictures.

When you get up, you can enjoy the picturesque view of the ocean and San Francisco as a reward. The best time to take great photos here is before sunset.< /review>

<Rate>4</Rate>< Text>
Gorgeous! Great views! It's the sets of stairs to get to the to, but even from the bottom, the view of the ocean is lovely. The gardens along the tiled stairs are super sweet, with many unusual succulents, most of which are labeled. Beware: there are signs throughout the neighborhood warning of car break ins.</Text>

114848446501799714678< /user_id>
< user_name>
Eric Tam</user_name>
< time>
1491784631746</time>
<rating>5< /rating>< Review>
Amazing place... You get breath taking views from the bottom of the stairs and as you climb the stairs the view only gets better. At the top, you are rewarded with sweeping views of the Sunset district with a cool fresh air breeze. Walk another block up and walk up another 100+ flight of stairs and the view gets better; you can see part of the golden gate bridge.

Be forewarned that the neighbors here are very respectful of their neighborhood so please keep it clean and don't steal the plants! Also this is a tourist attraction so keep your valuables out of sight.< /Review>

<date>1510466007592<//date><rating>5</rating><review>This is a hidden gem in the middle of a residential neighborhood. It's a community inspired effort, which came together to sponsor handmade animal mosaic tiles. A friend told me about the tiles and since then, I've brought others to take in the stunning handiwork. If you get to the top, you'll be rewarded with beautiful views of the city. Best pictures of the tiles can be taken during the day, but the sunset provides a scenic view. Either way, you won't be disappointed!< /review><pictures>None< /pictures><Resp>None<//Resp><GmapID>0x80858761c278b065:0x3d5b0419554cd6ed< /GmapID></record>

<user>106950827836679107334< /user><Name>CMoore Evil<//Name>< date>
1581393348156</date>
< Rating>
5< /Rating>
<Text>Remember, there's more than just one!

If you're like me and can't "relax" on a vacation, this is one little adventure that will certainly keep you on your feet and work those leg muscles. San Francisco's secret mosaic staircase is an exciting mini adventure that will kill about an hour or two of your day depending on how quick you move and how many of the steps you're looking to see. Not only are you going to see some amazing views of the city, you'll also get to take in the beauty of tile art as the flowing mosaic runs up 163 steps and swirls around for even more steps that lead up to Grand View Park.

Now, there's a few steps to take in all the steps that are accounted for with this escapade as most people only come for the middle steps on 16th Avenue (between Noriega St. & Moraga St.). But there is also another flight of stairs from the 15th Avenue Steps Park (corner of Kirkham St. and 15th Ave.). It's only a 5 minute walk between the two and the 15th Avenue Steps Park is certainly less crowded though overlooked I would guess since it's all under the shade of the trees and doesn't shine quite as bright.  These of course steer you to Grand View Park which offers massive views of the city and Golden Gate Park. All are definitely a hidden gem worth seeking out and conquering, plus it's another completely free escape from the city. Be sure to shout down upon the San Franciscans below.< /Text><pics>None</pics><resp>None< /resp><gmapID>0x80858761c278b065:0x3d5b0419554cd6ed<//gmapID></record></dataset><record>

Definitely worth a visit! Loved the vista from up top with the mountainous terrain on the right and the gorgeous blues of Pacific Ocean spanning the length of the horizon. If you're still on the fence as to whether to go as I was, I hope you decide to add this to your list of places in SF to visit! It went beyond my expectations and I'm glad I went!</review>

<Name>Crystal M<//Name><time>1486601039104</time><rate>5< /rate><review>163 steps. Yes, I counted.

This hidden treasure is located in a residential area in San Francisco. It does get crowded here with the workout groups and the tourists so just be prepared to dodge the runners and people taking pics.

If its not too busy, take the time to appreciate each individual tiled step. Its so creative and if you are into art, you will love it.

At the top of the stairs, if its not too foggy, you will catch an amazing view. Definitely worth the climb!

Great workout, great photo op, this is a must see in San Francisco!<//review><pics>None</pics><Response>None< /Response><GmapID>0x80858761c278b065:0x3d5b0419554cd6ed</GmapID></record></dataset><record>

<UserId.>110861742899996226596<//UserId.></record>
</dataset><record>
< text>
Really cool spot, one of those nice little pieces of public art that you show to any friends or family or just visitors from out of town.

It is exactly what the description says they are "Tiled Steps" and the tile pieces makeup nice pieces of art that range from the sun to the moon and the stars. It's about 6 flights of vertical stairs.

From the top of the stairs you won't see the art, it's not until you walk down the first flight of stairs do you see the big picture :)

Again, really awesome spot, it might be a little hard to find but as long as you have Google maps you'll be able to find it.<//text>

< Text>
Sketchy people on the stairs really ruined the moment for us. They wanted us to take a pic of them and we did but then they offered to take a pic of us... we said no, then heard them ask the next couple the same thing. They were definitely targeting us tourists!! We gotta stick together!!

The steps were cool, go to the top, hang a right, and you can continue to go higher up wooden stairs to the top of the city!! Pretty cool spot</Text>

<Review>One of the greatest views in San Francisco!

After trying to find this place for a while now, my friends and I finally got to come here. Parking wasn't a problem for us when we went. We conveniently found one literally across the street.

It was also perfect when we went because there wasn't a lot of people so we were able to take some great pictures. The steps were a workout but that's totally fine! On top of the stairs, you could see Moraga clearly and the beach.

<Rate>4</Rate><Text>Hidden attraction not listed in any major tourist forum or pamphlet. Started out as a local spot, getting more popular now. Parking isnt bad for a quick visit, neighbors street only, no parking structure. Beware of leaving valuables in the car as break ins are common, even during the day time. Expect to spend 30 minutes of you are coming the stairs and the hill for the view. Can be difficult to get a picture of just the stairs as people tend to take their timing climbing it, expect to have other people in your photos.< /Text>< Pics>

<user_name>Urian Chang< /user_name><userid>101666004202405530548<//userid><gmap_id>0x80858761c278b065:0x3d5b0419554cd6ed<//gmap_id><resp>None</resp>< Pictures>

<Time>1467048174697< /Time><text>*NOTE: You'll have to look for street parking in the neighborhood.

*TIP: Climb up past the stairs (to more stairs) and to the top of the hill. The view from there is pretty amazing. Be sure to wear a windbreaker; it's colder and more windy at the top.

PRO:
+ The stairs are well done with colorful mosaics.
+ Gorgeous view of the city and ocean. Picturesque angles at any point of the steps: bottom, middle, and top.

CON:
- It can get crowded, so snapping a good photo can be tricky.
- They are steps on a steep incline.
- Personally, I don't think it's worth going out of your way to visit.<//text>< rating>

< text>
If you're a tourist and have found these steps, great job. This is one of the true little gems that most miss...
There are approx 164 steps....I tried counting exactly, but I obviously miscounted because I got different numbers...dummy me!
Anyway, it's a nice little workout heading up the stairs.
Oh, once at the top, continue on to Grandview Park for some of the best views of SFO.
Yes, a 'few' more stairs to climb but certainly worth it....I promise ;-)
Also, check out some of the pics from the other reviewers...they are pretty good.
Have fun!!!</text>

<Rate>2</Rate><review>Nothing special about this place. It's a long staircase covered in bathroom tiles. The tiles on the vertical part of each steps have been decorated with tiles San Francisco style. It's home made. Be careful when, especially when descending those steps, as the neighborhood is often wet in the fog, and the steps become very slippery. The nice aspect about this place is that it's a nice break from this car-run city as it's only for pedestrians (of course). Otherwise not worth the detour.<//review><pictures>None</pictures><response>None</response>< gmap_id>

<Rating>5</Rating>< username>
Jay Hussein (Jayzakh)</username>
<Date>1506403537024<//Date><Text>Been in the bay area most of my life and I never visited this place until now. Holy moly, this is an amazing display of art! Now getting here can be difficult as the roads are narrow, a specialty of San Francisco. There is quite a few parking spaces available but be wary that since this is a tourist spot, you have a increase of car break ins so do not leave any valuables in plain sight.
Now there is a lot of steps to climb but each step is designed beautifully and there are several designs as you ascend the steps ranging from the ocean, moon and the sun. When you reach the top, if you turn around you are greeted with a bird's eye view of the whole ocean front......assuming it is not foggy.

But wait there's even more! past the hill is even more steps but you can go to the very top of the hill and either swing by the cliff side or even have a better view of almost a 360 view of San Francisco!< /Text></record></dataset><record>

<rate>3< /rate><text>Good views!<//text><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPExejltfwaNR4f5xKBEWhKaSktDk76CWaZ3pPh=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOU-HlCTCR5sdaNiX8V8zXgyG8vfmlO6DfHwu5D=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pics><Response>None</Response><Gmap_id>0x80858761c278b065:0x3d5b0419554cd6ed< /Gmap_id></record>

<response>None</response><Name>Tiffany C< /Name><gmap_id>0x80858761c278b065:0x3d5b0419554cd6ed</gmap_id>< Rate>
5<//Rate>
<Review>If you're into scenic viewpoints and free local landmarks, you definitely have to check out the 16th Avenue Tiled Steps. This local stairway is located on Moraga Street. Surprisingly, it was not too crowded when we decided to check it out. Definitely a lot easier if you park at the bottom of the steps; that way, you'll get to enjoy the view of the steps before you actually climb them.

Each individual step is already unique in its own way, but when you take the entire staircase in as a whole, all the steps come together seamlessly. It creates a really beautiful picture - very similar to the ebb and flow of the ocean. It's really awesome how there are these beautiful treasures hidden throughout San Francisco - who would have known?

Even better is after you climb the entire staircase, you're able to take in the view of SF from a higher vantage point. If you come around sunset, you'll really be able to see the city view with the soft, warm glow of the sun as it casts a shadow over SF before it becomes engulfed in darkness.

It'll be a bit difficult to get a good picture without anybody blocking the view or intruding in your photo, but it's worth the wait! There seem to be rushes of people to these tourist-y spots, so wait for a chance where the crowd seems to be minimal and grab your opportunity to get that shot!

tl;dr - Highly recommend you check this place out if you're in to scenic things to do in SF! You'll be glad you did.<//Review><userid>111786517743281339317< /userid><Date>1499823928891<//Date>< Pics>
None</Pics>

<userid>114151707652654713147</userid>< username>
Alexandra Mushinski<//username>
< time>
1467151678288</time>
< Rate>
2< /Rate>
<text>The 16th Avenue Tiled Steps Project (2003) was an artistic endeavor curated by Aileen Barr and Collette Crutcher and executed by community members to beautify the neighborhood.  The project started in January 2003, and the Golden Gate Heights Neighborhood Association and the San Francisco Parks Trust funded it.  In the short time since the mural was created, the surrounding area has become known for car break-ins and other minor crimes. The piece consists of small murals on each stair step, which form a large tiled picture of the sky swirling down into the ocean when viewed from below. There are images of the sun, moon, stars, waves, fish, seashells and more. The mural is made of tiled glass pieces, and at night the steps light up to create a glow-in-the-dark version of the image. In the decade or so since the steps have been installed, crime rates have significantly worsened in the area, partially due to its growing popularity with tourists and vacationers who are unfamiliar with the terrain. The Tiled Steps are an excellent representation of the ways in which displacement and gentrification have changed San Francisco‚Äôs political and social environment.

Large parts of the fear surrounding the people who may be likely to steal could be speculation.  In the current fear based climate brought on by media reports and growing distrust based on economic status, the upper class is becoming more likely to call the police before having any probable cause.  This can only lead to further violence committed against minorities who know those spaces as home. Displacement plays a large role in the recent increase in crime; the people who once formed the neighborhoods of San Francisco have begun to be removed from places they called home for decades and replaced with the white upper class that formed the tech boom. None of the spaces created for homeless youth, ethnic centers, or safe spaces for LGBT community members are being saved in the wake of the growingly gentrified new residencies.  With growing tensions and class separations, there are obvious reasons why crime rates would be rising in San Francisco‚Äôs current climate. Despite the anger coming from the residents of this neighborhood, they have to admit to their role in the rapidly changing urban environment. Communities tend to form themselves around commonalities, so when historically ethnic neighborhoods are invaded by outsiders unwilling to learn and adapt to that community, homogenization is inevitable.  When white residents move in to a neighborhood for cheap rent or to surround themselves with a specific culture, they fail to realize the effect they have on that environment.  Ethnic and creative communities are being forced onto the streets and treated like outsiders in the places they‚Äôve lived their whole lives.  The growing socioeconomic tension in San Francisco has as much to do with increasing crime rates as the so-called vagrants that are wandering the streets and stealing from tourists. If there weren‚Äôt pre-existing frustration and lack of resources for all community members, there wouldn‚Äôt be a need for petty theft crimes and loitering in these areas.

Despite the good-naturedness of the creator‚Äôs intentions when building the 16th Avenue Tiled Steps Project, the rapidly changing environment of the city overcame the artwork and turned it in to something far more politically charged than they ever could have thought it would be. Community was a large part of the creation and aesthetic decision-making process behind the artwork, but as the meaning of community changes with its surroundings, the steps seemingly cannot withstand their new neighbors. Until there‚Äôs a shift in the way community members communicate with each other to deal with problems by focusing on the preservation of culture and safe spaces as opposed to creating an environment of violence and fear, it is unlikely that the steps and their surrounding space will see peace anytime soon.</text>< pics>
